                      on the N-CD surface disrupts both the aggregation induced emission (AIE) and FRET mechanisms. This disruption leads to the restoration of N-CD fluorescence while simultaneously quenching the fluorescence of LA@Au NCs. Under optimized conditions, the fluorescence response ratio (F465/F670
                     ) is directly proportional to the concentration of GSH within a linear dynamic range of 0.1–90 µM, with a detection limit (S/N = 3) of 0.03 µM. This novel combination paves the way for the development of fluorescent probes for detecting various molecules and biomolecules.

ce:section.ce:para:
Gold nanoclusters (Au NCs) are highly valued in fluorometric measurements for their biocompatibility, strong photoluminescence, and colloidal stability [28,29]. These nanoclusters can undergo AIE effect, enhancing their fluorescence emission and making them ideal probes for measuring various substances such as metals [30], proteins [31], glucose [32], and viruses [33]. One common aggregation pattern of Au NCs is cation-induced aggregation [30]. For example, aluminum (Al3+
                     ) and zinc (Zn2+) cause the aggregation of glutathione-functionalized Au NCs as a result of the strong coordination interaction between the carboxyl group of glutathione (GSH) and Al3+

                     [34,35].
